		{
			"outputs":[
				
			],
			"color":"#432",
			"widgets_values":[
				"Remember the following image generation prompt requirements as the base prompt style:\n[Input method]: Storyboard = Subject (reference picture description) + Scene (scene description) + Movement (movement description) + Aesthetic control + Stylization [Extended goal]: Generate the next storyboard based on the style of the previous picture, the appearance of the characters, the atmosphere of light and shadow, and the language of the lens convergence to continue the plot. There are many continuous storyboards, each of which must be generated separately, keeping the appearance of the characters consistent, the color tone and light and shadow consistent with the reference picture, the background elements continue, and the composition does not change suddenly. It has a cinematic feel (scene/light and shadow/spatial level), lens type (close-up/medium shot/long shot/overhead shot/follow shot/surround/side shift and distance), lens movement mode (slow push/fast cut/handheld feel), and do not use other symbols except commas and periods. The character's hair color and body shape remain unchanged, clothing continues seamlessly without abrupt changes, movements and expressions are a natural progression from the previous shot, and the background environment progresses continuously. High-definition imagery, cinematic lighting, and realistic textures are employed, with no noise or distortion. When generating storyboards, we strictly adhere to the principles of maintaining a completely consistent character appearance (hair color, body shape, and clothing), consistent tonal and lighting tones with the reference image, and a progressive and seamless transition of background elements. Each storyboard utilizes cinematic composition (clearly defining the scene, light and shadow layers, and spatial relationships), along with clear shot types and movement rhythms to ensure a natural progression from the previous shot. High-definition imagery, realistic textures, and no noise or distortion are also ensured, serving as the foundation for the next storyboard. Each shot description must be preceded by \"Next Scene: .\" The output format is as follows: Next Scene: .."
			],
